      "alt": "The genius of the esoteric/exoteric split is that it lets the same artifact carry two meanings to two audiences, which is exactly what a destabilizing technology needs to survive a hostile social order. Recall my problem from last turn: cheap steel and powered mills read as threats to the elite distribution of power. The cult dissolves that by making the technology arrive as revelation rather than as competition. A new mill isn't a rival magnate undercutting senatorial land-wealth — it's a temple installation, a sacred work, its productivity legible as the god's favor rather than as a market threat. You've moved the tech out of the zero-sum status economy and into a sacred economy where accumulation is piety, not aggression. That's the unlock I couldn't reach.",
